  "opinion": "As a mechanic who's seen generations of students come through my shop, I've noticed how stereotypes about who belongs in STEM fields can hold people back. Stereotype threat isn't just a theory—it's the quiet anxiety that when you're reminded you're 'not like the others,' your mind starts to work against you. I remember a young woman who came in for a car repair, nervous about being the only girl in a field where men dominate. She kept checking her hands for 'mistakes' before starting work, worried she'd prove the stereotype that girls aren't good with mechanics. That's stereotype threat in action: the fear of confirming a negative belief about your group. It's real, and it's harmful. We absolutely should address it. In my shop, I've started talking openly about how everyone—regardless of gender, background, or experience—can learn to fix things. I share stories of my own early struggles with understanding complex engine parts, and I encourage students to ask questions without judgment. It's about creating spaces where people feel safe to be themselves. Schools and workplaces need to do more than just talk about diversity—they need to build trust and show that STEM isn't about being 'the smartest' but about having the patience and curiosity to figure things out. When we address stereotype threat head-on, we're not just fixing a problem; we're opening doors for everyone to thrive in fields that matter. After all, a good mechanic isn't someone who fits a mold—they're someone who can fix what needs fixing, no matter who they are.",
